             $PKILL processName\r\n                $BASH /opt/code/bin/application_starter.sh > /dev/null 2>&1\r\n            else\r\n                $ECHO \"Memory is under control\"\r\n        fi     \r\nsleep 60\r\ndone\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nJason','Linux Restart Process / Application When Memory Threshold Is Reached','','publish','open','open','','linux-restart-process-when-memory-threshold-is-reached','','','2013-07-24 14:57:51','2013-07-24 18:57:51','',0,'http://jasonralph.org/?p=72',0,'post','',0),(73,1,'2012-06-07 13:07:37','2012-06-07 17:07:37','Here I needed to kill a c++ process that was leaking memory in order to save the server from meltdown.  Very simple while loop that calls the external command \"free\" and parses it\'s output with awk to store a variable.  Pretty neat and it works.  \n\n<pre lang=\"bash\"#!/bin/bash\n# jralph@hap-capital.com \n# Server memory capacity 48GB\nPKILL=$(which pkill)\nECHO=$(which echo)\nthresHold=47000\n\n\nwhile true\n\ndo \n\n    highMem=$(free -m | awk \'/^\\-/\' | awk \'{print $3}\')\n    $ECHO $highMem\n        if [ $highMem -ge $thresHold ] \n            then \n                $ECHO \"We reached the memory limit\"\n                $PKILL processName\n            else\n                $ECHO \"Memory is under control\"\n        fi     \n\nsleep 2\n\ndone\n</pre>','Linux Restart Process When Memory Threshold Is Reached','','inherit','open','open','','72-revision','','','2012-06-07 13:07:37','2012-06-07 17:07:37','',72,'http://jasonralph.org/?p=73',0,'revision','',0),(74,1,'2012-06-07 13:08:37','2012-06-07 17:08:37','Here I needed to kill a c++ process that was leaking memory in order to save the server from meltdown.  Very simple while loop that calls the external command \"free\" and parses it\'s output with awk to store a variable.  Pretty neat and it works.  \n\n<pre lang=\"bash\"#!/bin/bash\n# jralph@hap-capital.com \n# Server memory capacity 48GB\nPKILL=$(which pkill)\nECHO=$(which echo)\nthresHold=47000\n\nwhile true